# Feature-Sliced Design Architecture Rules

## CRITICAL ARCHITECTURE RULES - NEVER VIOLATE

### Layer Import Hierarchy

**STRICT RULE**: Higher layers can ONLY import from lower layers.

```typescript
// ✅ ALLOWED - Higher to lower layer imports
import { Button } from "@/shared/ui";           // features → shared
import { User } from "@/entities/user";         // features → entities
import { UserForm } from "@/features/user";     // pages → features

// ❌ FORBIDDEN - Lower to higher layer imports
import { UserForm } from "@/features/user";     // shared → features
import { Dashboard } from "@/pages/dashboard";  // features → pages
import { Header } from "@/widgets/header";      // entities → widgets
```

### Public API Enforcement

**RULE**: All imports MUST go through index.ts public APIs.

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT - Using public API
import { UserCard, useUserQuery } from "@/entities/user";

// ❌ WRONG - Bypassing public API
import { UserCard } from "@/entities/user/ui/user-card";
import { useUserQuery } from "@/entities/user/api/user-queries";
```

### Cross-Feature Isolation

**RULE**: Features cannot import from each other directly.

```typescript
// ❌ FORBIDDEN - Direct feature-to-feature imports
import { AuthForm } from "@/features/auth";     // from features/user

// ✅ ALLOWED - Use shared layer or app layer
import { useAuthStore } from "@/shared/stores";
import { api } from "@/shared/lib/client";
```

## Slice Structure Requirements

### Standard Segment Organization

```
feature-name/
├── ui/           # React components (.tsx files)
│   ├── component-name.tsx
│   ├── component-name.stories.tsx
│   └── component-name.test.tsx
├── model/        # Business logic and state
│   ├── types.ts
│   ├── validation.ts
│   ├── store.ts (if needed)
│   └── constants.ts
├── api/          # Data fetching and mutations
│   ├── queries.ts
│   ├── mutations.ts
│   └── contracts.ts
├── lib/          # Feature-specific utilities
│   └── utils.ts
├── config/       # Configuration
│   └── constants.ts
└── index.ts      # Public API exports
```

### Public API Design Pattern

```typescript
// features/user-profile/index.ts
// ONLY export what other layers need
export { UserProfileWidget } from "./ui/user-profile-widget";
export { useUserProfile } from "./api/queries";
export type { UserProfile, UserProfileFormData } from "./model/types";

// DO NOT export internal implementation details
// ❌ export { UserProfileForm } from "./ui/user-profile-form";
// ❌ export { userProfileStore } from "./model/store";
```

## Layer-Specific Rules

### App Layer
- Global providers (QueryClient, Router, Theme)
- Global error boundaries
- Application-wide configuration
- Can import from ALL layers

### Pages Layer  
- Route components only
- Page-specific layouts
- Can import: widgets, features, entities, shared

### Widgets Layer
- Complex UI blocks combining multiple features
- Reusable across pages
- Can import: features, entities, shared

### Features Layer
- User scenarios and business logic
- Self-contained functionality
- Can import: entities, shared
- CANNOT import other features

### Entities Layer
- Business entities and data models
- Domain-specific logic
- Can import: shared only

### Shared Layer
- Reusable utilities, UI kit, libraries
- No business logic
- Cannot import from any other layer

## Naming Conventions

### File Naming
- Components: `PascalCase.tsx` (e.g., `UserCard.tsx`)
- Hooks: `camelCase.ts` (e.g., `useUserQuery.ts`)
- Types: `camelCase.ts` (e.g., `userTypes.ts`)
- Utils: `camelCase.ts` (e.g., `formatUtils.ts`)

### Directory Naming
- Use `kebab-case` for directories (e.g., `user-profile/`)
- Match feature/entity names exactly

### Import Aliases
- Always use `@/` prefix for absolute imports
- Follow layer structure: `@/features/auth`, `@/shared/ui`

## Validation Rules

### Pre-commit Checks
1. No cross-layer violations in imports
2. All exports go through public APIs
3. No circular dependencies
4. Proper segment structure maintained

### Code Review Requirements
- [ ] Follows FSD layer boundaries
- [ ] Uses public APIs only  
- [ ] No feature-to-feature dependencies
- [ ] Proper segment organization
- [ ] Clear separation of concerns